BM25-llava_documents.content: The citizens of Barbados had the most powerful passports in the Caribbean region as of July 2020. At that moment in time, the Barbadian passport received a visa free score of 161 points. Passports from St. Kitts and Nevis and the Bahamas ranked second and third, scoring 156 and 155 as of July 2020. Meanwhile, Chilean citizens were holders of the most powerful passport in Latin American region that same year.

BM25_documents.content: The number of upper secondary students in Denmark amounted to over 145 thousand students in 2019, which was the lowest number in eight years. Since 2009, however, the number of students in upper secondary education increased significantly from around 123 thousand in 2009 to over 150 thousand students in 2017. In Denmark, upper secondary education is divided into general upper secondary programs, which primarily prepare for higher education, and vocational upper secondary education and training programs, focusing on careers in a specific trade or industry. Free education The increase in number of upper secondary students has led to an increase in the number of students in higher education. Upper secondary education is free in Denmark, and the most common type of institution is gymnasium, where most students afterwards proceed to higher education institutions such as universities. When taking the whole population into consideration, however, the highest completed education for over one in four Danes was primary education, which is ten years of compulsory education in Denmark. Higher education in Scandinavia In Denmark, universities are by far the most popular institutions when undertaking a higher education, and in 2019, the number of registered university students amounted to nearly 150 thousand students. Considering the rest of Scandinavia, similar patterns appear. In Sweden the number of registered students grew overall the past decade, while the number of students in higher education peaked in Norway in 2019.
BM25_documents.title: Number of students in upper secondary education in Denmark from 2009 to 2019

Mistral-llava_documents.content: A good education and hard work are most often seen as the keys to getting ahead in life. This view is especially prevalent in emerging and developing nations, where most see economic opportunity expanding. Still, many also believe success can be determined by things outside a person’s control, such as luck or having a wealthy family.
Mistral-llava_documents.title: Education Important for Getting Ahead On a scale ofo to 10, how importantis to get ahead in life? Percent saying *10 very important"

Mistral_documents.content: Given other economic and environmental problems, however, education is not high on the minds of the Chinese public. In our 2013 survey, only 24% in China said education was a very big problem, which lagged far behind those who identified rising prices (59%), corrupt officials (53%) and the gap between the rich and the poor (52%) as major problems. However, the issue has picked up steam since 2008, when only 11% said education was a very big problem.
Mistral_documents.title: Education Not High on List of Public Concerns in China % very big problem

Mistral_documents.content: As 77 million kids prepare to head back to school in the coming weeks, the public says major changes are needed in the way the education system works in this country. Overall, 66% say either that the education system in this country needs to be completely rebuilt (21%) or that it requires major changes (45%); only 31% think the system works pretty well and requires only minor changes.
Mistral_documents.title: Views of the Education System

Mistral_documents.content: This statistic displays the government expenditure on education in the Netherlands in 2018, by level of education. It shows that the government spent approximately 14.8 billion euros on secondary education in 2018.
Mistral_documents.title: Government expenditure on education in the Netherlands in 2018, by level of education (in million euros)*

Qwen2_documents.content: In 2018, just over five percent of Dutch GDP was spent on education and student loans. GDP of the Netherlands amounted to roughly 737 billion euros in 2017. Expenditure on education as part of GDP peaked in 2010, at six percent. Absolute spend peaks in 2018 In absolute figures, government expenditure on education and student grants did not peak in 2010, but in 2018, at over 41 billion euros. In 2010, government spending amounted to approximately 35 billion euros. Expenditure by level Most of the government spending was spent on secondary education in 2018, at just under 15 billion euros. By comparison, the government only spent 8.9 billion euros that year on tertiary education. However, this is excluding the student loans, grants and allowances, which amounted to a further 4.4 billion euros that year.
Qwen2_documents.title: Government expenditure on education as share of GDP in the Netherlands from 2008 to 2018
